“Our Sea”: Inland Bolivia hopes the court will open its way to the Pacific Ocean
Marines patrol an equipped naval headquarters in La Paz.
Public buildings hang an ocean-blue flag.
The sea bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are painted with the motto: “The sea is ours by right.
We have to bring him back.”
In Bolivia, which has no access to the sea, there is still a living memory of the loss of the coastline that left Chile in the bloody conflict of the 19th century due to natural resources, and there is also a desire to swim again in the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes are now perhaps the strongest in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling from the international court on October 1 after five years of consideration of the case.
“Bolivia has a momentum, a spirit of unity and peace, and of course it expects a positive result,” said Roberto Calzada, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the announcement of the decision of the ICTY on large screens across the country. They hope that the tribunal in The Hague will make a decision in favor of Bolivia, which after decades of fragmented talks will force Chile to negotiate the grant of Bolivia a sovereign settlement.
Evo Morales, a charismatic indigenous Bolivian president who faced opposition to his re-election next year, also puts great hopes in a decision to be announced on Monday.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific,” he promised at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to make a decision in favor of Bolivia, and if that happens, little will change.
The United Nations body, based in the Netherlands, has no authority to allocate Chilean territory and noted that it will not determine the outcome of possible negotiations.
That the ICJ’s decision, taken only six months after the final arguments were made, indicates that the case “was not difficult,” said Pas Zarate, a Chilean expert on international law.
The case of Bolivia has not progressed, the last four years could have contributed to the retreat back.
“The issue of access to the sea was used by the current Bolivian administration,” Zarate said.
Morales’ military rhetoric undermined the remnants of Chilean kindness, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue the dialogue at some point, but after that it will be very difficult to hold discussions.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodriguez Velze, a representative of Bolivia in The Hague, disagreed with the fact that the court's decision was unusually rapid.
On Monday, Bolivia will have an “extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile and a chance to end 139 years of differences, with mutual benefit,” he said.
Calzada also denied that Morales — still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents — used the maritime issue as a political militia.
“Bolivia will never renounce its right of access to the Pacific Ocean,” he added.
This decision is an opportunity to see that we must leave the past behind.”
