John Edwards: Knowledge of languages is mandatory for the citizens of the world
Scotland’s independent schools maintain high standards of learning, and in 2018 again achieved excellent exam results, complemented by individual and collective success in sports, arts, music, and other fields.
These schools, which enroll more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, are represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SHRNSH). They strive to provide the best level of service for pupils and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further and higher education, their chosen careers, as well as making them citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can develop and implement an individual school program, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to a person in a language he understands, he perceives it with his mind.
If you talk to her in her native language, she takes it with her heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot use only English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the latest results of this year’s exams, we see that in independent schools, languages are leading in the rankings of subjects with the best ratings.
Overall, 68% of students who studied foreign languages received a higher score of A.
The data collected in 74 schools of the SRNSH showed that 72% of students received a higher score of A with Chinese, and another 72% of those who study German, 69% of those who study French, and 63% of those who study Spanish also received A.
This indicates that independent schools in Scotland consider foreign languages to be vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as a subject of choice are now taught in the same way as NTIM subjects (science, engineering, engineering and mathematics), as part of independent school programs and in other institutions.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills in 2014 found that 17% of the reasons employers can’t close job vacancies are related to lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary in preparing young people for future careers.
As more and more promising positions require knowledge of languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the chosen career, if someone has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future, because it is a lifelong skill.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a person who speaks several languages an advantage over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% could not speak a foreign language well enough to support a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a two-definition percentage of people (15%).
That’s why investing in language learning is important for today’s children.
Knowing several languages, especially the languages of developing countries, will provide children with a better chance of finding a full-fledged job.
In Scotland, each school will learn its own language.
A number of schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK from a 2020 perspective, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interests in independent schools, you will always be able to choose several languages to study with qualified teachers.
Scottish independent schools are trying to create an educational environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, regardless of what has prepared the future for them.
It is now undeniable that in the international business environment languages continue to be vital to the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
Modern languages should indeed be considered “skills of international communication”.
Independent schools will continue to provide this choice, diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
We have to do it.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
