North Korea says it will “in no way” disarm unilaterally without confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the UN on Saturday that the extension of sanctions deepens mistrust of the United States and that under such circumstances the country will in no way be able to give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho said at the annual UN General Assembly that last year, North Korea took “substantial measures of goodwill”, such as the cessation of nuclear and missile tests, the dismantling of the nuclear test site and the commitment not to disseminate nuclear weapons.
"However, we do not see any appropriate reaction from the United States," he said.
Without trust in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances we will not be the first to disarm unilaterally.
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s familiar complaints about Washington’s “step-by-step” approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea will be rewarded for its gradual steps, his statement was important because it was not unilaterally rejected.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between a real U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim called for work on the “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula” and Trump’s “people without guarantees”.
North Korea is seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang should first give up nuclear weapons.
Washington is also resisting calls to weaken tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The U.S. is insisting on ‘denuclearization first’ and raising the level of pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal by force, and even opposing the ‘declaration of an end to war’,” Ri said.
“To believe that sanctions can put us on our knees is the impossible dream of those who do not know us.
But the problem is that the continuation of sanctions deepens our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention the plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. leader stressed at the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister drew attention to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Zhe In over the past five months and added: “If the party to the denuclearization issue were South Korea, not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula is not too far away.”
Despite this, the tone of Ri’s speech drastically differed from last year’s when he told the General Assembly that North Korea’s missile targeting the U.S. mainland was unavoidable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim “a human-missile.”
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking disarmament measures, but said much more needs to be done and sanctions should remain in place until North Korea’s denuclearization.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not set a time frame for this: “It will take two years, three years or five months – it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia claim that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday, “Implementation of the Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and steadfastly until we see a complete, definitive, confirmed denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to block funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear programs and ballistic missiles.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for the second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was unsuccessful.
He left Pyongyang in July and commented that progress had been made, but a few hours later North Korea convicted him of "gangster demands".
During a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea promised to dismantle the missile complex, as well as the nuclear complex, if the United States takes "appropriate measures".
He said Kim said he needed "appropriate measures" to ensure the security that Trump had promised in Singapore and steps to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has provided all its students with more sleep. This is an attempt to combat the growing culture of learning cruising all night after caffeine refills.
The professor found that the number one university students in the world are often uneducated when it comes to the very basics of how to take care of yourself.
Charles Chassler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Women’s Hospital, has developed a course that he believes is the first such course in the United States.
He decided to start the course after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
In the end, one girl approached him and said, “Why are they telling me this right now, in my final class?”
“She told me that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was first introduced this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help achieve academic and sporting results, as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s medical services, said the university decided to introduce a course after it was found that students were seriously sleep deprived during the week.
The hourly course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a room in a dormitory where students click cups of coffee, curtains, exercisers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, the impact of sleep deficiency on athletic performance, as well as the importance of sleep-related routine.
Another section tells participants how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Next, a map of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not change the behavior of students instantly.
But we believe that they have the right to know, just as you have the right to know about the health consequences of smoking cigarettes,” Chassler said.
A culture of pride for “wake up all night” still exists, he added, noting that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean that the problem of sleep deprivation is on the rise.
A good enough sleep should be a student’s “secret weapon” to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, even with excess weight gain, as sleep deprivation translates the brain into a mode of hunger that causes constant physical hunger, he said.
Raymond Soe, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Chassler develop the course after enrolling in one of his other courses last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to create a new course for the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, will be to appeal to all graduates with a request to go through a similar program of study before entering a competitive institution.
Professor Chassler recommends that students be reminded that they should go to sleep, as well as put on an alarm clock and be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" that is emitted by electronic screens and LED lamps and can disrupt the circadian rhythm, leading to problems with the eyes.
