Almanach: inventor of Geiger's counter
And now the page from our almanach "Sunday Morning": September 30, 1882, 136 years ago on this day, and the time is passing... in Germany was born the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactive radiation, an invention that eventually evolved into a device known as the Geiger counter.
Since then, Geiger has become one of the key elements of science, as well as one of the key elements of pop culture, for example in the 1950 film Coronado Bells with Roy Rogers and Dale Evans, who play dubious cowboy scientists.
Husband: “What is that?”
Rogers: “This is a Geiger counter that is used to find radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you wear these headphones, you can really hear how radioactivity in minerals affects atoms.”
Evans: “Well, it’s really cracking right now!”
Hans Geiger died in 1945, just days before his 63rd birthday.
