The National Trust will observe the secret life of bats
A new study, which is being conducted on land in the Scottish Highlands, aims to establish how bats use the landscape in search of food.
Scientists hope that the resulting data will help shed light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals in order to take measures to preserve them in the future.
In the gardens of Inverness in Western Russia, scientists of the National Trust of Scotland will observe such species as the dwarf neptune and the pygmy neptune, as well as the ear of the ordinary and the water nightmare.
Special registrars will be placed in strategic locations on the territory of land ownership to monitor the behavior of bats during the season.
Employees and volunteers of the National Trust of Scotland will also conduct mobile research using handheld detectors.
An expert analysis of all recorded sounds will help establish the frequency and affiliation of bat screams.
It is then planned to develop a detailed animal habitat map and prepare a report to link animal behavior with their habitat environment.
Rob Dewar, an advisor on nature conservation at the National Trust of Scotland, hopes that the results of the study will help determine which habitats are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to assess the effectiveness of habitat care measures (e.g. meadow formation) and to identify optimal forest conservation methods for bats and other related species.
Over the last century, bat populations have declined significantly in Scotland and the United Kingdom.
They are threatened by the active construction and development of territories, depriving them of nest sites.
Other negative factors include wind turbines and lighting, adhesive paper for flies, chemical treatment of building materials, as well as attacks of domestic cats.
They are not actually blind.
However, by hunting at night, the ears help them catch prey more effectively than the eyes.
They use a complex echolocation technique to detect insects and obstacles on the flight path.
The National Trust of Scotland, which houses more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens of special significance and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bat problems very seriously.
Ten specially trained experts regularly conduct research, inspections of nesting sites and sometimes even rescue operations.
The organization's efforts even created the first and only bat reserve in Scotland. It is located on the territory of the Triv estate in the Damfries-and-Halloween region. It has found a shelter for eight of the ten species of bats that live in Scotland.
Managing Director David Thompson says this is the perfect place for them.
"On the territory of the site of Triv excellent conditions for bats," he assures.
"There are old buildings, many giant trees and other favorable living conditions.
However, we still need to learn a lot about bats. Thanks to the research we are doing here and elsewhere, we will be able to learn more about what they need to thrive."
He insists that it is very important to check the territory for the presence of bats before carrying out any technical work, because due to the accidental destruction of one nest site for the removal of the young may die up to 400 females with the young, which is likely to cause the destruction of the entire local population.
Species and their nests are protected by law. Animals are prohibited from killing, torturing or disturbing.
Elizabeth Ferrell, an officer at the Scottish Bat Conservation Center, urged the public to join the organization’s efforts.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats. We have not yet revealed the characteristics of the populations of many species."
