How a U.S.-China Trade War May Benefit Beijing
Experts believe that the first steps in a trade war between the United States and China were desperate, and, although far from its conclusion, in the long run, the split between countries could benefit Beijing.
U.S. President Donald Trump made his first warning shots earlier this year, taxing major Chinese exports, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The biggest escalation this week was due to new tariffs on goods totaling $200 billion (<0xC2><0xA3>150 billion), which actually taxed half of all goods coming into the U.S. from China.
Beijing has paid the same coin each time, recently imposing duties of five to ten percent on U.S. goods worth $60 billion.
China has committed to similar U.S. measures, and the world’s second-largest economy is unlikely to miss the opportunity to deliver on that promise in the near future.
To force Washington to retreat is to agree to the demands, but for Chinese President Xi Jinping, public worship of the United States is too shameful.
However, experts believe that if Beijing makes the right use of the situation, the pressure in the trade war with the United States could bring China advantage in the long run, reducing the relationship between the two economies.
“A swift political decision in Washington or Beijing can create conditions that will lead to a sharp economic downturn in any of the countries. And it actually poses a greater threat than observers have acknowledged before,” said Security Analyst Abigail Grace, who is involved in the Center for Asian Affairs.
The foreign minister said that Syria "ready" for the return of refugees
Syria says it is ready to voluntarily return refugees and seeks help to rebuild a country devastated by more than seven years of war.
Speaking to the General Assembly of the United Nations, Foreign Minister Walid al-Mualem said that conditions in the country are improving.
“Today, the real situation has become more stable and safer thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rebuild areas destroyed by terrorists so that people can return to normal life.
All conditions have been created for the voluntary return of refugees to a country that they had to leave because of terrorism, as well as unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives and limited the means of subsistence.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country are in need of humanitarian aid.
Al-Muhammad said the Syrian government would be pleased to accept assistance to rebuild the war-torn country.
But he stressed that they will not accept conditional aid or aid from countries that support the uprising.
