Current information about the red tide: a decrease in concentration in the districts of Pinellas, Manat and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Commission on Fish and Wildlife indicates a general decline in the level of red microorganism bloom in some parts of Tampa Bay.
According to the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, the abundant flowering conditions reported in certain areas of Pinellas, Manat, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties indicate a decrease in concentration.
The flowering of red microorganisms extends for approximately 130 miles of the coastline from the north of Pinellas to the southern districts of Lee.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but they are less than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week it was reported about the average concentration in Pinellas County and in its coastal zone, the concentration from low to high in the coastal zone of Hillsboro County, the high concentration in Manat County, the high concentration in Sarasota County, the high concentration in Sarasota County and in its coastal zone.
In the districts of Pinellas, Manat, Sarasota, Lee and Collier continue to report respiratory irritation.
There were no such reports recorded in the northwest of Florida last week.
